# DB Migration Safety — Schema Changes Kill Production

A bad migration can lock a table, corrupt data, or take down your app for hours. This rule forces you to think before you alter.

## Before writing any migration file

Answer these out loud:

```
MIGRATION BRIEF
───────────────
What is changing: [table name, column name, operation]
Why it is changing: [the reason — not "because it was asked"]
Is this destructive: YES / NO
  (Destructive = DROP, RENAME, TYPE CHANGE, removing NOT NULL, shortening VARCHAR)
Estimated rows affected: [rough count if known]
Can this be rolled back in under 5 minutes: YES / NO
```

If destructive is YES and rollback is NO — stop. Redesign the migration.

## Required steps for every migration

- [ ] Migration is written as a separate file — not inline in application code
- [ ] Migration has a corresponding rollback / down function
- [ ] Migration tested on a local or staging environment before production
- [ ] If adding a new NOT NULL column — it has a DEFAULT value, or is added in two steps (nullable first, backfill, then add constraint)
- [ ] If dropping a column — the application code no longer references it in ANY query before the migration runs
- [ ] If renaming a table or column — a compatibility alias or two-phase rename is used, not a single rename in one deploy

## Index rules

- [ ] Every new foreign key column has an index
- [ ] Every column used in a WHERE clause on a large table has an index
- [ ] No index added on a large production table without `CONCURRENTLY` (PostgreSQL) or equivalent — this blocks writes
- [ ] Composite indexes are ordered by selectivity — most selective column first

## The two-deploy rule for destructive changes

Never drop a column or table in the same deploy that removes the code referencing it.

```
Deploy 1: Remove all code that reads or writes the column
Deploy 2: Drop the column
```

This gives you a safe rollback window.

## After the migration runs in production

- [ ] Verify row counts are what you expected
- [ ] Verify the application is not throwing errors related to the changed schema
- [ ] Verify query performance on affected tables has not degraded
- [ ] Document the change — what changed, why, and when

## The rule in one line

If you cannot roll it back in 5 minutes, you are not ready to run it.
